00:00:07.419 --> 00:00:11.250
No matter how serious, every movie is made
with the assumption that fans will be looking

00:00:11.250 --> 00:00:16.320
at the exact characters, objects, or action
that the director intends. But sometimes,

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:21.199
people wind up watching anything but. Whether
it's overzealous extras, subtle jokes, or

00:00:21.199 --> 00:00:24.690
mistakes from the crew, sometimes watching
the background of a movie scene can be twice

00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:28.869
as much fun. If you like this video make sure
you stick around until the end for links to

00:00:28.869 --> 00:00:33.230
more videos like this one! Here are Screen
Rant's 10 Hilarious Details Hidden In Popular

00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:36.300
Films.

00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:37.300
The Godfather

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:42.930
In a perfect world, movie audiences would
never even notice a background actor, since

00:00:42.930 --> 00:00:47.139
they should be invisible - if they're doing
their job. The Godfather is hailed as one

00:00:47.139 --> 00:00:52.249
of cinema's greatest films, but even IT falls
victim to one hilarious blown take, thanks

00:00:52.249 --> 00:00:56.819
to an extra who steps into frame well ahead
of her mark. Once you see her pop into view

00:00:56.819 --> 00:01:02.679
and quickly sneak back out, you'll notice
it every time.

00:01:02.679 --> 00:01:06.140
Gladiator&nbsp;

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:10.430
Director Ridley Scott had to rely on computers
to recreate Rome's massive Colosseum, and

00:01:10.430 --> 00:01:14.229
the thousands of spectators sitting inside
it. But background extras were also needed

00:01:14.229 --> 00:01:19.140
for closer scenes, which opened the door to
some less-than-historic cameos. Like the audience

00:01:19.140 --> 00:01:22.509
member creeping over his fellow Romans to
make sure he gets into the entire frame of

00:01:22.509 --> 00:01:25.990
the camera that really isn't supposed to be
there.

00:01:25.990 --> 00:01:32.039
The Hobbit: Battle of The Five Armies

00:01:32.039 --> 00:01:35.929
Peter Jackson's trilogy may star a Hobbit
and a squad of Dwarves, but it's the Elves

00:01:35.929 --> 00:01:43.740
who show up to help save the day, with thousands
and thousands of soldiers, too. The Hobbit

00:01:43.740 --> 00:01:48.630
Trilogy took some flack for using too much
CG, but that wasn't a problem for this scene:

00:01:48.630 --> 00:01:53.450
every single one of the elves is given the
exact same face, copied and pasted over and

00:01:53.450 --> 00:02:01.009
over again. Unless elves mastered cloning,
it's one massive detail the effects team overlooked.

00:02:01.009 --> 00:02:03.549
Speed

00:02:03.549 --> 00:02:08.069
Getting a city bus up to 50 miles per hour
isn't easy in any situation, but threatening

00:02:08.069 --> 00:02:12.870
to blow it up did the job for Speed. The action
takes place on freeways, city streets, and

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:16.849
even an airport, with the constant threat
of an explosion keeping viewers' eyes stuck

00:02:16.849 --> 00:02:21.390
on the bus. It's a good thing, too - otherwise
they might notice the cameraman filming the

00:02:21.390 --> 00:02:26.450
action, not even&nbsp;trying&nbsp;to stay hidden from
prying eyes.

